mediaNotes: NOTES: A GROUP OF 5-6 CANVASBACKS COURTING AMONG THE LARGE FLOCK OF AYTHYA AMERICANA, ANAS STREPERA, ANAS ACUTA, ANAS CLYPEATA, ETC. ON THE SMALL LOWER POND. WHEN THE MALE CALLED HE OPENED HIS BILL SLIGHTLY AND GAVE A SINGLE 'CUCK'. WHEN HE THREW HIS HEAD BACK TO HIT HIS BACK AND THEN CAME FORWARD AGAIN, HE GAVE THE SOMEWHAT LOUDER 'CUCK-COO' AS A SWELLING THE SIZE OF A MARBLE FORMED BENEATH HIS BILL. THE FEMALE DID NOT OPEN THEIR BILLS BUT I THINK THE ACCOMPANYING CHATTER WAS MADE BY THEM. P.P. KEL. Number of individuals=AU5-6;. Other Behaviors: Court, Perform Visual Display. Habitat: Pond.

Interesting snorting noise at about 1 min 20 sec., 1 min. 40 sec., 2 min. and some other times.  I cut some of the Canada Goose calls.

The wing sound at 40 sec is definitely canvasback taking flight (along with a COGO call), and I believe the strange calls at 2 sec, 25 sec, and 32 sec, are female canvasback preparing for a short flight. I was recording pintail and I head these strange calls. As I was was trying to figure out what it was, a female canvasback took off for a short flight around the lake. I listen to the sounds on this lake a lot (maybe too much) and I've never heard this call before. But then again I can't find anything on ebird or xeno canto to match it
